## Test Anti-Pattern Audit: `UserRepositoryTests`

**Summary: 3 Critical · 2 High · 1 Medium · 3 Low** — This class is the likely root cause of your incident. Half the tests give false confidence.

---

### 🔴 Critical — Tests giving false confidence

**1. No assertions — `GetUser_NonExistentId_ReturnsNull` (line 20–24)**

The test retrieves a user and does nothing with it. It always passes.

```csharp
// ❌ Before
var user = repo.GetById(999);
// should be null

// ✅ Fix
var user = repo.GetById(999);
Assert.IsNull(user);
```

**2. Swallowed exception — `AddUser_DuplicateId_ThrowsException` (line 27–39)**

The `try/catch` pattern silently passes whether or not an exception is thrown. If `Add` stops throwing, this test still passes.

```csharp
// ✅ Fix — replace entire method body
var repo = new UserRepository();
repo.Add(new User(1, "Alice"));
Assert.ThrowsException<InvalidOperationException>(() => repo.Add(new User(1, "Bob")));
```

**3. Always-true assertion — `DeleteUser_RemovesFromRepository` (line 42–48)**

`Assert.AreEqual(repo.Count, repo.Count)` compares the value to itself. This can never fail.

```csharp
// ❌ Before
Assert.AreEqual(repo.Count, repo.Count);

// ✅ Fix
Assert.AreEqual(0, repo.Count);
```

---

### 🟠 High — Likely to mask bugs

**4. Broad exception type — `AddUser_NullUser_ThrowsArgumentNullException` (line 71–75)**

Name says `ArgumentNullException` but asserts `Exception`. In MSTest, `ThrowsException<T>` checks exact type match — this test likely **fails** as-is, or if it passes, any exception satisfies it.

```csharp
// ❌ Before
Assert.ThrowsException<Exception>(() => repo.Add(null!));

// ✅ Fix
Assert.ThrowsException<ArgumentNullException>(() => repo.Add(null!));
```

**5. Negative-only assertion — `UpdateUser_ChangesName` (line 51–58)**

`Assert.IsTrue(user.Name != "Alice")` only checks the name *changed*, not that it changed *correctly*. If `Update` set the name to `null` or `""`, this test still passes.

```csharp
// ❌ Before
Assert.IsTrue(user.Name != "Alice");

// ✅ Fix
Assert.AreEqual("Alicia", user.Name);
```

---

### 🟡 Medium / 🔵 Low

| Sev | Location | Issue | Fix |
|-----|----------|-------|-----|
| Medium | `GetUser_ExistingId_ReturnsUser` | Weak assertion — only checks `IsNotNull`, not that the correct user was returned | Add `Assert.AreEqual("Alice", user.Name)` |
| Low | Line 8 | Unused static `HttpClient` — never referenced, also `IDisposable` not disposed | Remove the field |
| Low | `SearchUsers_ByPartialName` | `Console.WriteLine` leftover from debugging | Remove it |
| Low | `SearchUsers_ByPartialName` | `Assert.IsTrue(x == 2)` gives poor failure messages | Use `Assert.AreEqual(2, results.Count)` |

---

### ✅ Positive observations

- `GetAllUsers_ReturnsCorrectCount` is well-written — checks count *and* verifies each item
- Naming convention is consistent (`Method_Scenario_Expected`)
- Each test creates its own `UserRepository` — good isolation, no shared mutable state

### Priority

Fix the **3 Critical** findings first — these are almost certainly the tests that passed while the production code was broken. Then address the 2 High issues to prevent the same class of incident from recurring.
